# gh Auth First

Always verify `gh` authentication before running any GitHub CLI command.

## Rules

1. Run `gh auth status` before any `gh` subcommand.
2. If the output shows "not logged in" or is missing required scopes (e.g. `repo`, `workflow`), stop and ask the user to run:
   ```
   gh auth login
   ```
   Then re-run `gh auth status` to confirm.
3. Never run destructive or mutating `gh` commands (e.g. `gh pr create`, `gh issue create`, `gh release create`) until auth is confirmed as OK.

## Examples

```bash
# ❌ BAD — running gh pr create without checking auth first
gh pr create --title "Fix bug" --body "..."

# ✅ GOOD — check auth first, then proceed
gh auth status          # confirm logged in and scopes include "repo"
gh pr create --title "Fix bug" --body "..."
```

If `gh auth status` fails mid-session (e.g. token expired), prompt the user to re-authenticate with `gh auth login`, then retry the original command.
